If it is set to true the Guardian credit limits are loaded when the trader login is processed by RegisterUser. There is currently no client application that needs this value set to non-zero. In fact setting it non-zero would break TTRelays spanning different networks.

Number of contracts sent in response to a pricetable or contract download request. Valid values are positive. Values less than 1 use default.

Set to 0 (default) to have the currently active price server handle the requests. Set to 1 to have the standby price server handle the requests (if standby server goes down requests aren't handled until it comes back up). Set to 2 to have standby handle product requests unless none is running then active handles requests.
Sets the amount of time after which a market depth update from the exchange is considered to be invalid. For polling exchanges. Omit or set to -1 to indicate that depth updates never expire.

Sets the amount of time (in milliseconds) between price updates. Inside Market updates arriving within this interval are cached; only the latest update is retained (except for Last Traded Price and Last Traded Quantity which are queued). Market Depth updates arriving within this interval are queued. When the coalescing interval time elapses or an internal buffer limit is reached (whichever comes first), all updates are published. An interval value of 0 (the default) turns off all queuing.

The flag used to turn on/off detail depth support. 0 means turn off detail depth support, 1 means turn on detail depth support. 0 is used as default. If this value is missing, it will treated as 0 inside gateway.

The flag used to turn on/off limiting the levels of depth sent to clients. The full depth is still maintained on the server. Set to -1 (default) to send all available levels of depth. Depth levels start at 1 (inside market).

A value of true instructs the server to look for tokens in the contract download request and short circuit the download if a matching token is found in its product/price tables. Do not modify this setting unless instructed to do so by TT Support.

A value of true instructs the server to generate price updates in the PFX mode. A value of false indicates TTAPI formatted price updates. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Milliseconds. Controls the interval at which Non-TradeData updates are being naggled and broadcast onto the wire. A value of 0 disables Non-TradeData nagling so that all updates are broadcast immediately. This setting is used only when PFXEnabled is set to true. In the PFXConverted GW that outputs legacy TTAPI price updates NTD coalescing follows the same model as the selected PDD type. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Microseconds. Controls the interval at which Non-TradeData updates are being throttled within an NTDUpdateInterval. A value of 0 disables the throttle so that all queued NTD updates are sent immediately. This setting is used only when PFXEnabled is set to true and when NTDUpdateInterval is greater than 0. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Set to true to log in price server log file price request/subscription and VAP requests/subscriptions from non-PFX clients when the server is converted to PFX. The requests will be rejected if the server is operating in the PFX mode as well.

A value of true instructs the server to listen for price download requests and generate price download packets on the price service area, thus joined in the TCP stream with regular price updates. A value of false indicates legacy behavior. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Selects a mode of Prioritized Data Delivery (PDD). A value of -1 indicates that the setting of Market-Depth.Interval-mSecs should be queried and used if set. A value of 0 means no PDD at all. 1 indicates IO Decoupling PDD. Further settings for this type are collected in the PDD.IODecoupler block. A value of 2 indicates Time Based Decoupling PDD. A value of 3 indicates Strict Timer Coalescing PDD. Further settings for types 2 and 3 may be specified in the PDD.Coalescing block. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.
A number of distinct queues (threads) used when a specific PDD mode is selected. Not used when PDD is set to 0 (off). Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.
Count. The maximum number of EchoTimeout periods. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Seconds. The minimum period of time passed prior to resending a TradeData update when no market updates are received from the exchange for a product. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. A maximum number of Exchange price updates that will be processed before a TradeData message in response to a contract snapshot request will have been broadcast. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. A maximum number of Exchange price updates that will be processed before a TradeData message in response to a market depth modification will have been broadcast. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. A maximum number of Exchange price updates that will be processed before a TradeData message in response to an inside market modification will have been broadcast. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. A maximum number of Exchange price updates that will be processed before a TradeData message in response to a price modification resulting from a completed trade will have been broadcast. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. Indicates how many times the output thread should give up the CPU before deciding that a GW is not processing any new inputs. When idle GW is detected pending TradeData updates will be broadcast onto the network immediately. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Milliseconds. The minimum period of time between broadcasts of consecutive TradeData updates resulting from snapshot requests. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Milliseconds. The minimum period of time between broadcasts of consecutive TradeData updates resulting from market depth updates. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Milliseconds. The minimum period of time between broadcasts of consecutive TradeData updates resulting from inside market updates. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Milliseconds. The minimum period of time between broadcasts of consecutive TradeData updates resulting from completed trades. Any price data modifications applied during this interval will be reflected (coalesced) in the broadcast update message as well. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. Indicates how many additional Exchange price updates a TradeData update that has reached its update rate interval will attempt to collect before broadcasting a TradeData message onto the network. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Count. Indicates how many times the output thread should give up the CPU before deciding that a GW is not processing any new inputs. Pending TradeData updates that have reached the update rate they were scheduled for will be broadcast onto the network immediately when idle GW is detected. This setting is similar in use to PDD.IODecoupler.IdleDetectCount. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Set to true to allow pending contracts from a given product to be sent in the same message at the time any single contract from that product is sent out (either as a result of an immediate send or when the priority interval has expired). Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.
A value of true will truncate long price subjects. A value of false will not truncate price subjects. Do not modify this setting unless specifically instructed to do so by TT Support.

Defaults to false. When set to "true", order servers will connect to all order routers of the same gateway flavor on all workstations; thereby sharing the order book for all order routers to all permissioned traders. This setting is required for remote order router configurations. Setting this value to "false" will cause the order server to only communicate with order routers on the same workstatin as the order server.
Defaults to 64 order routers. Determines the maximum number order routers to be configured by this order server.
Defaults to false. When set to "true", upon initialization, order servers will only search for local routers. "False" will enable remote routers to be used.
Defaults to false. When set to "true", order server will reject all orders that were not risked checked on the client.

Configures how often (in seconds) the price server will broadcast the exchange and gw times to subscribed clients. On GWs that poll the exchange this directly affects how frequently the exchange is polled. A value of 0 turns off this feature. Recommended values are 60-300. Increasing the frequency of updates does not improve the accuracy of times unless there is substantial clock drift on the GW workstation.

Exchange-Day-Start is the hour:minute:second of the start of the trading day, in local exchange time. It is ok to omit minute and second, they default to zero. If data is missing or invalid Exchange-Day-Start defaults to midnight. Note: If this value is changed, the Price, Order, Order Routers, and Fill Servers must ALL be restarted so they will remain in synch with each other as to rollover time.

StandardStart and DaylightStart are month,week,weekday,hour:minute:second representing transition date and time to standard or daylight time. Month is 1-12, week is 1-5, representing the first to last week of the month, weekday is 0-6, Sunday=0. It is ok to omit minute and second - they default to zero. If data is missing or invalid, USA standards are used. Example: USA daylight time begins the first Sunday in April, at 2AM: DaylightStart=4,1,0,2:00:00 Example: USA standard time begins the last Sunday in October, at 2AM: StandardStart=10,5,0,2:00:00

StandardBias and DaylightBias are the hour:minute:second difference from UTC. It is ok to omit minute and second - they default to zero. (local+bias=UTC) Example: USA CentralStandardTime is 6 hours behind UTC: StandardBias=6:00:00 Example: USA CentralDaylightTime is 5 hours behind UTC: DaylightBias=5:00:00

Exchange-Day-Start is the hour:minute:second of the start of the trading day, in local exchange time. It is ok to omit minute and second, they default to zero. If data is missing or invalid Exchange-Day-Start defaults to midnight. Note: If this value is changed, the Price, Order, Order Routers, and Fill Servers must ALL be restarted so they will remain in synch with each other as to rollover time.

StandardStart and DaylightStart are month,week,weekday,hour:minute:second representing transition date and time to standard or daylight time. Month is 1-12, week is 1-5, representing the first to last week of the month, weekday is 0-6, Sunday=0. It is ok to omit minute and second - they default to zero. If data is missing or invalid, USA standards are used. Example: USA daylight time begins the first Sunday in April, at 2AM: DaylightStart=4,1,0,2:00:00 Example: USA standard time begins the last Sunday in October, at 2AM: StandardStart=10,5,0,2:00:00

StandardBias and DaylightBias are the hour:minute:second difference from UTC. It is ok to omit minute and second - they default to zero. (local+bias=UTC) Example: USA CentralStandardTime is 6 hours behind UTC: StandardBias=6:00:00 Example: USA CentralDaylightTime is 5 hours behind UTC: DaylightBias=5:00:00

Whether or not the Total Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP) feature of the Price Server is active. This feature is required by X_TRADER's MD_TRADER to visually display Traded Quantity at each depth price.

The granularity at which to pidgenhole prices (LTP) for the purpose of keeping Total Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP). Incoming price updates from the gateway will be rounded to the nearest value (subject to the rounding policy, "TTQAP.Rounding-Policy") evenly divisible by the value you specify here. The default is '1'. The units for TTQAP.Granularity are the same as for LTP, and the TTQAP logic completely ignores any tick size information associated with the LTP.

Must be set to either "round_up" or "round_down", the only two policies supported by the Total Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP) logic. The policy controls the affinity (up or down) for incoming prices when quantizing them per the "TTQAP.Granularity" value. The meaning of each value is self-explanatory.
The number of seconds to allow to elapse between writes of the Total Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP) checkpoint file, from which TTQAP recovers in case of a price server restart.
The number of milliseconds to wait between sends of Total Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP a.k.a. VAP) updates.
If true, additional debugging entries will be made to the Guardian log for Traded Quantity At Price (TTQAP a.k.a. VAP) activity on the server side.
The period, in days, which must elapse before the price server will mark a product as stale and stop tracking its value-at-price information.

When set to "true", TTQAP values are reset daily at the time specified in the server specific Time.Zone section of AConfig. When set to "false", TTQAP reset is triggered by an exchange event. NOT ALL GATEWAYS FUNCTION CORRECTLY WITH A VALUE OF FALSE. If this value is set to false for a Gateway that is not equipped to handle a setting of false, TTQAP values for that Gateway will never be reset.

Indicating if gateway provides implieds for spreads Possible values are: 0 no implied prices are available 1 implied prices are merged into inside mkt best bid and best ask prices and quantities 2 implied prices are not merged into inside mkt best bid and best ask prices and quantities but are delivered into implied bid and implied ask prices and quantities.

Indicating if gateway provides implieds for outright Possible values are: 0 no implied prices are available 1 implied prices are merged into inside mkt best bid and best ask prices and quantities. 2 implied prices are not merged into inside mkt best bid and best ask prices and quantities but are delivered into implied bid and implied ask prices and quantities.
Gateway expects quotes to be supplied as orders If not supplied or supplied and set to zero the gateway expects quotes to be supplied via the quote structures
Supported Products for this gateway. See enum ProdIDs for all the product types. A value of 78 (1001110) means FUTURE(1), SPREAD(2), OPTION(3) and BOND(6) are supported.
The gateway supports delivery of Market Depth information - either aggregate or detailed. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero the gateway does NOT support market depth

Setting indicating whether the last traded qty is NOT accumulated for all trades that occur at that price A value of 1 indicates that the last traded Qty value is the quantity of only the last trade (qty is not accumulated). A value of 0 indicates that the last traded qty is the sum of all trades that occured at that price value.

Setting indicating whether the site_order_key field in the order structure is persisted with the order in normal operation. A value of 0 indicates that the site order key is supplied to the client from the GW with order-related callbacks. A value of 1 indicates the site order key is not supplied to the client with order-related callbacks.

The permutations of order group deletes supported by the gateway. This is a string containing comma separated integers. Each integer represents a valid combination of deletes supported natively by an exchange. The value is a bitset whose index is: 0 = delete by price, 1 = delete by put/call, 2 = delete by bid/ask, 3 = delete by series, 4 = delete by product, 5 = delete by trader. Consequently, a integer value of 48 implies delete all orders for specified trader and product combination (for all series, bid/ask, put/call, and price combinations). If this tag is not supplied or supplied and set to zero the gateway only supports deletes by single order

Setting indicating the meaning of the member field in market depth If not supplied or supplied and set to zero the field is not available. A setting of 1 indicates account number, 2 indicates firm id, 3 indicates order number.
Setting indicating whether stop limit orders are supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, stop limit orders are supported. A value of 1 indicates stop limit orders are not supported.

Setting indicating whether stop market orders are supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, stop market orders are supported. A value of 1 indicates stop market orders are not supported.

Setting indicating how order cancels order type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, order cancels order is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how iceberg type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, iceberg is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how growler type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, growler is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how block type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, block is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how basis type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, basis is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how volatility type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, volatility is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how market on open type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, market on open is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how market on close type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, market on close is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating how flex option type is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, flex option is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the manner in which it is supported: 1=EUREX, 2=LIFFE, 3=CBOT, 4=CME, 5=ENXTFUT, 6=ENXTOPT, 7=ISLAND, 8=XETRA, 9=IB, 10=Synthetic.

Setting indicating whether batch processing of orders is supported. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero, batch order processing is not supported. Values greater than zero indicate the order actions that can be batch processed. The value is a bitset: 0=add, 1=change, 2=delete, 3=hold, 4=inquire, 5=update, 6=replace, 7=resubmit. See class GALSetOfBitsets and enum GAL_BATCH for additional data

Setting indicating whether or not a gateway process is a simulated exchange. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero clients should assume the gateway is not simulated. Non zero values indicate a simulated gateway, such as TTSIM.
Setting indicating at what frequency a gateway price server supplies exchange time update information in seconds. A value of zero indicates the gateway does not support this feature.

Setting indicating that prices in market depth data contain only direct bids and asks (it has no implied bids or asks). If not supplied or supplied and set to zero clients should assume the GW feed contains implied price data.

Setting indicating that inside market price data contains only direct bids and asks (it has no implied bids or asks). This applies to TT_BEST_BID_PRC, TT_BEST_BID_QTY, TT_BEST_ASK_PRC and TT_BEST_ASK_QTY price types. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero clients should assume the GW feed contains implied price data.
Setting indicating that the gateway (and client) supports fills for spreads in addition to fills for the legs. This flag is only relevant in fill api clients.

Setting indicating that the gateway may send prices in the inside market price feed which are not tradable and will be rejected if submitted to the host in an order. A setting of 0 (or unspecified) indicates that all prices are tradable. A setting of 1 indicates that all prices in the feed may NOT be tradable.

Setting indicating that the exchange provides fills in either passive or aggressive mode. A setting of 0 (or unspecified) indicates that passive/aggressive is not supported. Setting indicating how the exchange matches implied orders. If not supplied or supplied and set to zero no implied matching is performed. Set to 1 if outrights will match implieds from calendar spreads and their outrights. Calendar spreads and butterflies will match implieds from outrights. Condors do not match implieds at all. Implieds from implieds will match. (LIFFE and NQLX behavior) Set to 2 if outrights will match implieds from calendar spreads and their outrights only. Only classic implieds (not implieds from implieds) match.(Eurex and CBOT behavior) Set to 3 if outrights will match implieds from calendar spreads and their outrights. Implieds from implieds will match.
